[1mSummary of the recipe:[22m[0m[0m
[0m[0m
- **The Problem:** Explains why one-size-fits-all population health management fails, and why behavioral segmentation based on actual utilization patterns is more actionable than static cost tiers.[0m[0m
- **The Technology:** Covers feature engineering from claims data, normalization strategies for skewed healthcare data, algorithm selection (K-Means, GMM, HDBSCAN), dimensionality reduction with PCA, and validation approaches for unsupervised learning.[0m[0m
- **General Architecture Pattern:** Vendor-agnostic pipeline from claims data through feature engineering, normalization, clustering, profiling, and operational deployment.[0m[0m
- **AWS Implementation:** SageMaker for ML pipeline, S3 data lake, Glue for ETL, Athena for analysis, DynamoDB for real-time lookup, QuickSight for dashboards.[0m[0m
- **6-step pseudocode walkthrough:** Extract, engineer features, normalize/reduce, cluster, profile/name segments, store assignments.[0m[0m
- **Expected Results:** Sample 6-segment output with realistic benchmarks.[0m[0m
- **The Honest Take:** Covers the "so what?" problem, segment instability, denominator issues, cost feature traps, and mandatory equity audits.[0m[0m
- **Variations:** Temporal trajectory clustering, segment-specific predictive models, real-time assignment for new members.[0m[0m
